<foil>
<title>The semantics question</title>

<itemizedlist>
<listitem>
<para>Web pages aren't just human-readable, they're also machine readable</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>Expressing semantics in a <emphasis>machine-understandable</emphasis> way is
harder (more markup)</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>But the result (can be) clearer because the semantics are more explicit</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>If you're starting from rich XML sources, many of the semantics may already
be manifest or implied</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>The trick is to encode them for web pages</para>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist>
</foil>

<foil>
<title>Semantic quest</title>

<para>Consider this example: you're looking for a kitten picture to
put on your blog. You find this:</para>

<programlisting language="xml"><![CDATA[<img src="photo1.jpg" alt="An example photo" />]]></programlisting>

<para>What might you need to know?</para>

<itemizedlist>
<listitem>
<para>Who took it?</para>
</listitem>
<listitem>
<para>Is it licensed for reuse?</para>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist>

<para>After all, the ones you can't reuse aren't very useful for your
current task.</para>

<para>Ideally, if you could these questions machine understandable,
you could filter on them.
</para>
</foil>

<foil>
<title>Semantic examples</title>

<para>RDFa:</para>

<programlisting language="xml"><![CDATA[<img src="photo1.jpg"
  rel="license"
  resource="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/"
  property="dc:creator" content="Mark Birbeck" />]]></programlisting>

<para>HTML5/Microdata</para>

<programlisting language="xml"><![CDATA[<span itemscope="itemscope">
  <img itemprop="about" src="photo1.jpg">
  <link itemprop="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml/vocab#license" 
        href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/">
  <meta itemprop="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/creator" 
        content="Mark Birbeck">
</span>]]></programlisting>

<para>This is a hot topic, I don't think the dust has fully settled yet.</para>
</foil>

